IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: **Incident recorded by issued body worn camera** ATTACHMENTS: -Copy of the MVA printouts VICTIM/ COMPLAINANT: -David Lawrence Davis Sex: Male Race: White DOB: 11/22/1964 -Jerid Levi Davis Sex: Male Race: White DOB: 11/02/1992 -Diane Crowe Sex: Female Race: White DOB: 01/10/1965 WITNESS: -Ronald James Crowe Sex: Male Race: White DOB: 10/24/1965 SUSPECT: -Ashley Nicole Davis Sex: Female Race: White DOB: 11/01/1986 -Michael Scott Cassady Sex: Male Race: White DOB: 01/22/1965 NARRATIVE: On September 17, 2023, at 1326 hrs, I, Senior Trooper K. Preston (#6305) responded to 12002 McMullen Highway for a report of a burglary/theft from a storage shed. I arrived at the residence and met with the victims, Jerid Levi Davis and David Lawrence Davis, at the storage shed behind the residence. Jerid advised his sister, Ashley Nicole Davis and an unknown accomplice(s), had broken into two storage sheds and stole lumber and tools. Jerid confronted Ashley about this, and he stated Ashley told him she wasnt the one who took the items, but she allowed people to take it. Both Jerid and David advised Ashley has a substance abuse problem that was most likely the driving force behind the theft. They advised Ashley left on foot prior to my arrival walking southbound on Route 220. Jerid then showed me the sheds. One shed had a garage door that can only be opened by a key that Jerid and David have. A window on the left side was broken and appeared to be the entry point. David owns the shed that the louvered style window was broken out of (window valued at $50) and Jerid owns the tools that were taken. Jerid provided a list of the items he identified as stolen and their value. The list includes a Craftsman chop saw (valued at $100), a tile saw (valued at $50), a paint gun (valued at $20), a Craftsman toolbox containing miscellaneous hand tools (valued at $100), and a carpet stretcher (valued at $93.00). Jerid was unable to provide any serial numbers and advised the tools were given to him by his late grandfather. Jerid advised that in a smaller shed, there was approximately 80 boards of cherry wood lumber that was 1X6x8 ft and 1x12x8 ft (valued at $20 a piece totaling $1,600). Total value of the items taken is $1,913. Jerid and David advised Ashley lives in the house, but did not have access to the sheds. Jerid said that the last time he was at the shed was approximately a month ago. Jerid and David came to check the residence after finding out someone attempted to break into Davids mothers residence in City of Cumberland earlier in the day. They suspected that Ashley was involved and came to the residence and discovered the broken window. They advised that at the broken window was a ladder that they removed and placed in Davids truck. Ashleys fourteen-year-old son, Brylan Levi Davis, was with Jerid and David. They advised Ashley kicked him out of the house over this incident. Jerid said for the time being, Brylan was going to stay with him. Jerid advised the neighbor, Ronald James Crowe, had witnessed a van at the shed. I went to 11918 McMullen Highway and spoke with Ronald in the driveway adjacent to his residence. He was accompanied by his wife, Diane Lynn Crowe and Felicia Lynn McKenzie. Ronald advised on Friday, September 15th between 1300 hrs and 1400 hrs, he observed a blue van with front end damage and Maryland historic license plates backed up to the window that was broken. He said there was a male that he did not recognize with the van. On Saturday, September 16th, at approximately 1600 hrs, Ronald observed a brown SUV with Maryland license plates. He stated there was a male different from the male with the van, but still did not recognize him. Ronald said he observed Ashley help the male load a chop saw in to the SUV. Ronald said on September 11th he observed the window to the shed was partially broken, but said it was still open enough for someone to crawl through. Ronald said days later he saw the window was completely broken as it is now. Diane advised on Thursday, September 14th, at approximately 1745 hrs, Ashley knocked on their door and ask her if she wanted to buy a paint gun set for $30. Diane also stated her Mongoose mountain bike was stolen from under their deck. Diane advised that her and Ronald were out of town from September 3rd to the 10th. They realized the bike was gone when the returned. They suspect Ashley might have taken it but did not want to pursue with anything further. Diane advised she just saw Ashley at the Route 220 park and ride prior to coming home. I then went to the park and ride in an attempt to locate Ashley and was unsuccessful. Dispatch advised that David had called in and advised Ashley was back at the residence. At 1402 hrs, I returned to the residence and interviewed Ashley (full interview captured by my body worn camera). Ashley was in Davids truck and began to exit the truck as I walked up and introduced myself. Ashley asked if we could move up to the houses back porch so she could sit down. I agreed to moving to the porch. As we walked, I confirmed it was Ashley and asked if she knew why I was here. She replied yeah and sat down on the steps leading up to the porch. I then asked her why am I here, and she replied cause I broke into that shed. As she said this she looked at the sheds and nodded in their direction. Ashley stated she was on drugs and that was her reason for breaking into the shed. When asked who was in the blue van she gave the name Mike Cassady. During the course of the interview Ashley stated she gave the tools to her cousin Josh Heimlich, but was not sure on the pronunciation of the last name. She said she lent him the tools so he could build his daughter a tree house and that he lives in Grantsville, Maryland. I asked her what she got in return for all the tools, and she replied, A cap of dope. I then stated, One cap of dope for all those tools? and she nodded yes. I asked her why Josh did not come to Jerid and ask to borrow the tools, and she replied they dont like him [Josh]. I asked her, So you break the window and get him the stuff? and she nodded yes. I asked her how many times she went into the shed to steal the tools, and she held her left hand up with just her index finger extended. I said it was more than once because one time she broke the window a little referring to Ronalds statements about the window being partially broke, and I stated one time she broke the window more. She replied, My hair got stuck, implying that from her crawling through the window, her hair got stuck and caused the window to break more. I asked about the paint gun, and she said that it is at her boyfriends, Luke Ginevans mothers house in Paw Paw, West Virginia. Ashley advised that Mike Cassady was her only accomplice and that there was no one in a brown SUV. I advised Ashley if this is true she needed to get the tools back and return them to Jerid. Ashley advised Ginevan was currently in the hospital. I advised Ashley that I will be applying for charges against her for this incident. I concluded the interview with Ashley. I went back to Jerid and David at the sheds. They were in the process of putting up a piece of wood to block the broken window. I asked them if they knew of a Josh Heimlich and they said no. I conducted a search of law enforcement database and discover Ashley was associated with a Michael Scott Cassady. An MVA check revealed Cassady has a 1999 Plymouth Voyager registered to him. At 1927 hrs, I went to Cassadys residence at 12508 Bowling Street. At the rear of the residence was a carport with a Blue Plymouth Voyager van (MD Registration:754Z94) matching the description of the van that was seen parked at the window of the shed. I at first knocked on the front door and was advised by Cassadys sister that he lives in the basement with a rear entrance. I then went around the back of the residence. As I approached the back door, Cassady opened it and stepped out. I interviewed Cassady in the carport area (full interview captured by my body worn camera). Cassady claimed to not have any part of the theft even after I advised him that his vehicle was seen there and Ashley stated he assisted her. Cassady said that Ashley wanted to take a container of tattoo equipment to pawn today. He advised that he told her since it was Sunday no pawn shop was open, but he said he drove her around. Throughout the entirety of the interview, Cassady kept bringing up the tattoo equipment and events that occurred today even after I advised him multiple times that I was not concerned with the tattoo equipment and todays events. I ended my interview with Cassady and advised I will be applying for charges against him for this incident. I conduct a check of the pawn databases and was unable to locate any of the stolen items at this time. All the above events occurred in Allegany County, Maryland. I request this case remain open pending application for charges.

Attachments: -Copy of bother served warrants Narrative: On September 18, 2023, I completed an application for charges for Ashley and Cassady and submitted it to the Allegany County District Court Commissioner. The commissioner issued an arrest warrant for both for the following charges: Second degree burglary times two, theft $100 under a $1000, malicious destruction of property less than $1,000. On September 19, 2023, at 0848 hrs I served the arrest warrant on Ashley at her residence (12002 McMullen Highway SW, Cumberland MD 21502). She was transported to Allegany County Detention Center to await her initial appearance before the commissioner. On September 19. 2023. at 1049 hrs I served the arrest warrant on Cassady at his residence (12508 Bowling Street, Cumberland MD 21502). He was transported to Allegany County Detention Center to await her initial appearance before the commissioner. Charges: Second degree burglary (X2) (Felonies) Theft $100 under a $1000 Malicious destruction of property less than $1,000 All events occurred in Allegany County, Maryland. I request this case be closed by arrest.
